{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Apolipoprotein CII (apoC-II) is a surface constituent of plasma lipoproteins and the activator for lipoprotein lipase (LPL). It is therefore central for lipid transport in blood. Lipoprotein lipase is a key enzyme in the regulation of triglyceride levels in human serum [[cite:PUB00010498]]. It is the C-terminal helix of apoC-II that is responsible for the activation of LPL [[cite:PUB00029348]]. The active peptide of apoC-II occurs at residues 44-79 and has been shown to reverse the symptoms of genetic apoC-II deficiency in a human subject [[cite:PUB00010498]].</p>\n\n<p>Micellar SDS, a commonly used mimetic of the lipoprotein surface, inhibits the aggregation of apoC-II and induces a stable structure containing approximately 60% Î±-helix. The first 12 residues of apoC-II are structurally heterogeneous but the rest of the protein forms a predominantly helical structure [[cite:PUB00025907]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR023121", "name" "ApoC-II domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR16566" "APOLIPOPROTEIN C-II"}, "pfam" {"PF05355" "Apolipoprotein C-II"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Apolipoprotein C-II", "short" "Apo-CII"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 4, "domain_architectures" 5, "proteomes" 237, "taxa" 1074, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 410, "sets" 0, "proteins" 407, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 263}, "pathways" 22}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR008019", :literature {"PUB00010498" {"URL" nil, "issue" "2-3", "authors" ["Storjohann R" "Rozek A" "Sparrow JT" "Cushley RJ."], "ISO_journal" "Biochim. Biophys. Acta", "DOI_URL" "http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S1388-1981(00)00062-7", "medline_journal" "Biochim Biophys Acta", "title" "Structure of a biologi